<paragraph id="5A353D0214BF2E98662F6C5497CCAFB3" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="853D5373CEDAAB2912BA89FE9C01E812" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
MEXICO. Hidalgo, Cumbre de Jacala, 
<emphasis id="3661EB0EBC8D4CFC6DCAF5406165D562" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">E. Matuda</emphasis>
37288 (holotype MEXU00050769).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6F515C277ACE1F9158D4BDCCC2680FA1" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="description">
<paragraph id="6E8C1015BDF35F53A7427FF45BB782A4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="66FB8883BBAADA5F8F1041A39F8810B7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Trailing or climbing plant, stems finely pilose, glabrescent. Leaves petiolate, 4-9 
<normalizedToken id="3D3089132BDF65EF85C813E343FDB625" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.5-7 cm, ovate-deltoid, obtuse, base cordate and then cuneate onto the petiole with distinct rounded auricles, margin irregularly dentate, both surfaces green, abaxially paler, strongly reticulate, veins pubescent; petioles 2-5 cm. Inflorescence of 1-3 flowered, axillary cymes; peduncles 10-15 cm; bracteoles 1-4.5 
<normalizedToken id="6E2BF81C03FE60B1025B947D2FE88435" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5-3.5 cm, ovate, petiolate, dentate, resembling small leaves; pedicels 14-22 mm, tickened upwards, pubescent; sepals subequal, 15-17 
<normalizedToken id="B87C0C4E6A39942AC1E25F5CB9514E92" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6 mm, narrowly oblong-elliptic, acuminate, margin scarious, outer sepals pubescent, glabrescent; corolla 5.5-6.5 cm long, funnel-shaped, pinkish-purple with paler tube, glabrous, limb c. 3 cm diam. Capsules and seed unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1D86B62595ADC4BA150547648FAD6FF5" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="25D031B35B7D12A95663807B9E328E45" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B275A44D068E502E4109474A95A9AFFB" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Endemic to Hidalgo in Mexico and only known from the type.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="50876EA209AB18CDA25CD98BB37F2D7D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="7124688FA981C708747B1A1F4FF22C6F" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">MEXICO. Hidalgo</emphasis>
: type collection.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="575A64FC5997AF59F88BE4718883F146" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="DBBF0036C6203E817C2377B162FC6E4C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7A632114086A9F709F214672C8638566" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The leaf shape suggests this species is intermediate between 
<taxonomicName id="F7ABCEA744BFCCB4C8F36E9799F44146" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stans">
<emphasis id="4B0C7F8FC0E321388E7BC559887E0A39" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea stans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and another species, perhaps 
<emphasis id="D6E675B376E871B0EFC4A9EF4FB1F272" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="DD60ED9901F560458AC5BE5E442B53B9" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="orizabensis">I. orizabensis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The foliose bracteoles and dentate leaves are distinctive characters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
